      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To anyone following the lawsuit seeking voting rights for Puerto Ricans (news article, Oct. 8), the obvious question is this: If they want to vote, why not petition for statehood?</p>
        <p>Here's one answer: Just before the last Puerto Rican referendum on status, in 1998, a former governor (who opposes statehood) announced that a victory for statehood would mean full federal taxation, long before admission into statehood. No transition, no gradual introduction, just whammo: full federal taxes overnight.</p>
        <p>This is untrue, of course. But in a place where local taxes rise as high as nearly 40 percent, it was an effective claim.</p>
        <p>Scare tactics designed to defeat statehood are a staple of Puerto Rican politics. As long as Congress refuses to define the options and work out the terms of a transition, the colonial status quo will prevail for all the wrong reasons.</p>
        <p>N. D. ROBERTSON  Chicago, Oct. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
